WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.130 --> 00:00:04.690
BILL DUANE: So
welcome everybody.

00:00:04.690 --> 00:00:08.330
We have some folks here
in the room, and then

00:00:08.330 --> 00:00:11.220
lots of folks on Livestream.

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:13.150
This is a continuation
of a program

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:18.040
we did a week and a half ago
on self-care and mindfulness

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:23.290
in particular, the role of
compassion and self-care

00:00:23.290 --> 00:00:25.570
and mindfulness.

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:26.920
And so this is needed now.

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:30.320
So my name is Bill Duane, and
I look after the Well-Being

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.270
and Sustainable Performance
programs here at Google.

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:37.010
And during my
team's team meeting,

00:00:37.010 --> 00:00:41.970
we took time to do a check-in
on how is our own well-being.

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:45.720
And for many of us, most of us,
actually, it was pretty bad.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:49.240
It was sort of remarkably bad.

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:51.250
Lots of emotional distress.

00:00:51.250 --> 00:00:54.360
And just to put a name to
it, the particular cause

00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:58.640
for the distress was
two further incidents

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:02.110
of black men being
killed by police

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:05.629
and the issues of systemic
racism in our justice system

00:01:05.629 --> 00:01:08.790
that that represents.

00:01:08.790 --> 00:01:10.290
And then, of course,
there have been

00:01:10.290 --> 00:01:14.080
the sort of like litany
of other stuff going on.

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.720
It just seems like every
time you watch the news,

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:19.610
the rate of these things
is rapidly increasing.

00:01:19.610 --> 00:01:22.120
So not all of us,
but a number of us

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:27.310
felt sort of distinctly not OK.

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:31.610
And on top of that, given that
we're the well-being team, when

00:01:31.610 --> 00:01:33.900
we unpacked it, we
realized that we felt bad

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:35.744
about feeling bad, right?

00:01:35.744 --> 00:01:37.910
We're just like, oh, I don't
want to feel like this.

00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:39.480
We shouldn't feel like this.

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:42.300
And of course then it's
possible to feel bad about that.

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:45.390
And it's feeling bad
all the way down.

00:01:45.390 --> 00:01:48.000
So one is, I just wanted to
start off the introduction just

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.650
acknowledging that if
that's where you're at,

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:51.480
you're not alone.

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:54.960
It seems like there's
something really different

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:59.080
and-- this is an odd way to
use the word-- but special

00:01:59.080 --> 00:02:03.040
about this time that makes
it something different.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:06.060
And that specialness
has a lot of potential

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:08.100
to think differently
about the way things are.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:11.220
But in the short term, there's
also the very practical need

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:15.130
to tend to our
internal experience

00:02:15.130 --> 00:02:19.060
so that we can show up in
the world the way we want to.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:23.030
So this talk is going to
focus on the expertise

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:25.120
of our presenters, which
is to say mindfulness,

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:29.270
and in particular,
mindfulness and compassion.

00:02:29.270 --> 00:02:34.810
But I also want to note that
mindfulness is not the only way

00:02:34.810 --> 00:02:35.770
to deal with these.

00:02:35.770 --> 00:02:39.250
In particular, connecting
with friends and family

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:41.690
is a great way of self-care.

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:42.690
Exercise.

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:43.690
Sleep.

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:46.490
Sleep is amazingly
supportive for this.

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:48.350
So there's probably a
number of other things

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:49.940
that are supportive
for you, and I

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:52.300
encourage you to really
pay attention to those

00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:54.210
and make time for those.

00:02:54.210 --> 00:02:55.840
But for this
session, we're really

00:02:55.840 --> 00:02:59.750
going to be focusing
on mindfulness

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:01.650
as a means toward self-care.

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:03.940
And one thing I
want to point out

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:07.140
is that we're talking
about self-care

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:09.770
not as a way of
numbing or escaping,

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:11.930
although it's really reasonable.

00:03:11.930 --> 00:03:14.130
When you feel bad,
you're just like, well,

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:17.562
I would like to feel better,
please, as soon as possible.

00:03:17.562 --> 00:03:19.270
And some of the
strategies for doing that

00:03:19.270 --> 00:03:22.329
are sort of suppressing
and turning away.

00:03:22.329 --> 00:03:24.870
The real thing that's amazing,
what we're talking about here,

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:29.490
is this idea of actually
turning towards the difficulty

00:03:29.490 --> 00:03:32.740
and turning towards your
internal experience.

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:35.740
But that's sort of a radically
counter intuitive, right?

00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:36.950
So how do you do that?

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:38.860
How do you do that
when you feel bad?

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:42.550
And the answer is, compassion.

00:03:42.550 --> 00:03:47.520
Compassion allows you to
hold difficult experiences

00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:50.360
in a way that can keep
you focused on it,

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:52.570
but also focused
on other people.

00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:56.550
And normally when we
experience strong emotion,

00:03:56.550 --> 00:03:58.210
we're a puppet to that emotion.

00:03:58.210 --> 00:04:00.770
It's sort of stimulus response.

00:04:00.770 --> 00:04:03.320
By cultivating the
skills of self-awareness,

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.350
self-management, and
compassion, when you experience

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:10.180
these internal
feelings of discomfort,

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:12.370
you can actually
put a little bit

00:04:12.370 --> 00:04:15.272
of a pause in there between
stimulus and response.

00:04:15.272 --> 00:04:16.730
There's a great
Victor Frankl quote

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:18.810
of "In between
stimulus and response,

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:20.290
there's the capacity
for a pause.

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:24.080
And in that pause lies the
chance for our freedom."

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:26.510
So that's what we're
talking about today.

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:29.470
And once you're free of
that sort of automaticity

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:32.480
of behavior, then something
beautiful happens.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:34.310
And the beautiful
thing that happens

00:04:34.310 --> 00:04:37.530
is the opportunity to act
in the world in a way that's

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:39.780
in alignment with your values.

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:41.810
And this is the way
that we can both tend

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:45.540
to our internal experience while
also making the positive change

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:47.020
in the world that we want to.

00:04:47.020 --> 00:04:50.970
It's this idea of an
engagement with ourselves

00:04:50.970 --> 00:04:53.430
and with our communities
and with the systems

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:55.430
that we're a part
of it while also

00:04:55.430 --> 00:04:57.210
tending to our own self-care.

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:59.077
So that's obviously
a pretty tall order.

00:04:59.077 --> 00:05:01.160
So I'm about to hand it
off to two friends of mine

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:05.550
so they could do the
actual work of this.

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:07.370
It's sort of radically
counter intuitive.

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:10.070
So I have two dear friends.

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:13.830
One is Sharon
Salzberg, who is really

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.640
one of the meditation OGs.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:19.790
She's one of the first people
to bring vipassana practice

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:22.700
in the current wave
to the United States

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:27.110
and really do a bunch of quite
beautiful translation of this.

00:05:27.110 --> 00:05:30.910
She is one of the founders
of the Insight Meditation

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:32.840
Society in Barre,
Massachusetts, which

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:35.060
is one of the preeminent
vipassana centers

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:37.730
and schools in the west.

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:39.920
She is also the "New York
Times" bestselling author

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.430
of books like "Real Happiness,"
"Real Happiness at Work,"

00:05:42.430 --> 00:05:44.750
"Real Happiness at the Dry
Cleaner," "Real Happiness

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:46.050
While Taking Out the Garbage."

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:47.590
No.

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:50.710
Getting back to real books now,
is "Loving Kindness" and a book

00:05:50.710 --> 00:05:52.990
on loving your enemies.

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:54.830
And one of the
things that I really

00:05:54.830 --> 00:06:00.370
enjoy about Sharon as a
student and also as a friend is

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:05.560
deep wisdom and knowledge
from some of the source wisdom

00:06:05.560 --> 00:06:07.470
traditions that these
practices come from.

00:06:07.470 --> 00:06:09.850
She really knows her stuff.

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:12.010
But it also seems
very real to me.

00:06:12.010 --> 00:06:15.860
Like Sharon is also a New
Yorker who has seen some shit.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:17.920
And there's an earthiness
and a saltiness

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:20.570
to the way that she
teaches that I find really

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:24.555
necessary, because my
relationship with compassion

00:06:24.555 --> 00:06:26.680
has to exist in the real
world, and that real world

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:30.250
as is far from perfect,
as I started off with.

00:06:30.250 --> 00:06:32.570
Also joining us
is my other friend

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:38.000
Phoenix Soleil, who is
a longtime meditation

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:38.924
practitioner.

00:06:38.924 --> 00:06:40.340
She is also an
expert in something

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:43.120
called nonviolent
communication, which

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:44.980
is a class that's
available from time

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:47.430
to time here in Mountain View.

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:51.600
And let me know if you would
like the contact information.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:57.990
She also offers coaching
and meditation mentorship.

00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:00.290
She is also a teacher in
training at Spirit Rock, which

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:06.790
is one of the other preeminent
vipassana centers in the United

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:07.790
States.

00:07:07.790 --> 00:07:11.360
And she is also a New Yorker
who has seen some shit.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:15.150
So I should also point
out that I'm from Queens.

00:07:15.150 --> 00:07:22.390
So we seem to have quite
the group of New Yorkers

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:25.790
representing in this area.

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:29.820
So please join me in welcoming
Phoenix and Sharon, who

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:34.420
will be leading us in some
practices and a little bit

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:36.510
of lecture and also
some exercises.

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:37.120
So thank you.

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:40.053
This is was put together at
extremely short notice again,

00:07:40.053 --> 00:07:42.420
Phoenix.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:44.880
So thank you very
much, and welcome.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:47.140
PHOENIX SOLEIL: I'm so
happy to see all of you.

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:51.450
And I was really grateful
to be here a couple few days

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:55.060
ago at the New York office.

00:07:55.060 --> 00:07:57.950
And it's interesting.

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:00.400
I was telling a lot
of people that I

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:05.180
noticed that after
doing that hour,

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:09.540
I noticed that I wasn't as--
I didn't feel as helpless when

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:12.410
I would read the news because
I had done something that

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:15.430
was in connection to my values.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.410
And I just want
to compliment all

00:08:17.410 --> 00:08:20.030
of you for coming
together here today

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:23.050
and people who are joining
us, because you're taking time

00:08:23.050 --> 00:08:28.060
in your day to put some
attention on some really

00:08:28.060 --> 00:08:29.370
difficult subjects.

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:32.570
Like I think one
of the ways that we

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:36.789
habitualized to deal with things
is push them away, you know?

00:08:36.789 --> 00:08:38.710
And there's nothing
wrong with that,

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:42.110
because sometimes you have
things you need to do.

00:08:42.110 --> 00:08:43.140
People have families.

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:44.230
You have jobs.

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:48.240
And sometimes you just can't
handle the feelings inside,

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:51.750
and it might be really
intelligent and smart to take

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:55.670
some time and say, I'm not
going to deal with this,

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:59.800
and I'm going to do whatever
is really urgent in my life.

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:05.140
What we know is that over time
there's a consequence to that.

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:06.820
It costs.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:12.420
There's the stress involved,
because it's still there even

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:13.800
if we're not looking at it.

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:17.479
And that space that we're
putting it to gets full.

00:09:17.479 --> 00:09:19.770
If we keep putting things in
it, it keeps getting full.

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:23.900
And then something small
happens with someone we love,

00:09:23.900 --> 00:09:26.700
and we might lose our temper.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:30.160
Or we cut someone off in
the highway, and you know,

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:31.230
it just builds up.

00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:34.610
And then it becomes
like a volcano.

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:39.270
And we know, we see on the news
some of the effects of people

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:41.680
having volcanoes inside.

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:45.910
So right here you're doing
the difficult human job

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:50.780
of coming and facing the pain.

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:54.270
The other thing, though--
on the other hand,

00:09:54.270 --> 00:09:59.190
the other way that we can
handle something difficult--

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:01.680
is to fall apart.

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:04.020
And I think that's what
causes-- a lot of us

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:05.100
choose the other one.

00:10:05.100 --> 00:10:07.200
I'd rather push it
away than fall apart.

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:09.390
I'm afraid of being
so overwhelmed

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:11.640
that I won't function.

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:13.670
And as a New Yorker,
it's been bred into me

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:16.350
that I have to function.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.470
You know, I've seen
all the "Rocky" movies

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:22.860
and I know that I'm supposed
to just get up there, put it

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:25.850
all to the side and win the
gold or whatever championship.

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:31.330
So those are the two pieces.

00:10:31.330 --> 00:10:35.980
But then that falling apart,
does that help anyone?

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:38.890
You know, it's so
beautiful that as a human

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:41.530
we are affected by things.

00:10:41.530 --> 00:10:47.170
But is that going to-- it's
beautiful, that sensitivity.

00:10:47.170 --> 00:10:48.920
And we see what happens
when people aren't

00:10:48.920 --> 00:10:51.590
connected to their sensitivity.

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:54.330
So what is the answer here?

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:56.250
And this is one of
the practice that

00:10:56.250 --> 00:10:58.630
creates this other space
that's in the middle, which

00:10:58.630 --> 00:11:00.220
is equanimity.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:04.520
This creates this space where
you can process the pain,

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:08.210
and you can be with
it in this loving way.

00:11:08.210 --> 00:11:12.590
And what you get to be is
able to see the big picture.

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:15.770
You're not consumed
by it-- and this

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:20.710
is how I sometimes feel-- and
you're not pushing it away.

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:25.477
And that is what we're
creating, and it takes time.

00:11:25.477 --> 00:11:27.060
We have a culture
where it's like, you

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:28.560
want to take a quick pill.

00:11:28.560 --> 00:11:35.870
And the quick pills don't
end up creating more safety

00:11:35.870 --> 00:11:39.010
in this society,
for us internally

00:11:39.010 --> 00:11:42.330
and for other people around us.

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:46.730
So I'm just going to check
in if there was anything

00:11:46.730 --> 00:11:49.720
I wanted to start with.

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:54.170
The other important piece is
that sometimes taking that time

00:11:54.170 --> 00:12:00.190
to do that self-care
can feel so selfish.

00:12:00.190 --> 00:12:06.420
We want to do things, but
this is the preparatory work,

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:10.390
because when you're having a
conversation from that pain,

00:12:10.390 --> 00:12:12.520
are you really open
to hearing someone?

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:14.530
Can you really bring
compassion to them

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:16.590
when you don't have
compassion inside?

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:19.010
When there's all this,
like, oh my god, I

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.250
can't stand this,
a lot of times we

00:12:21.250 --> 00:12:23.600
don't have the
resource that we need

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:26.790
to be able to sit and think and
really look at the big picture.

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:30.510
Because I think the problems we
have, there aren't quick fixes.

00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:33.720
These are these slow solutions.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:35.590
They need the long range.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:39.200
And I want to start with a sit.

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:43.080
And I want us to come into this
room and come into our bodies.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:48.610
And it's interesting that
we talk about running away,

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:53.720
because I think focusing
on the breath is

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:57.890
a healthy way of running away,
in a way, because you are

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:00.040
connecting to your body
and you're connecting

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:09.800
to the experience of
being a human right now,

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:11.620
right now in this moment.

00:13:11.620 --> 00:13:16.320
And whatever thoughts
you have about things,

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:19.850
you can put them on the
side for a little bit, OK?

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:23.010
So I'm going to ask
you to close your eyes.

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:25.630
If you don't feel comfortable
closing your eyes,

00:13:25.630 --> 00:13:29.500
you can put your attention
on the floor or something

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:33.040
neutral like the wall.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:37.230
And if you find
that what's inside--

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:38.720
you can keep your eyes open.

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:40.540
That's one of the suggestions.

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:44.920
And there's many kinds of
breaths that you can use.

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:48.914
I like this-- we're going
to take a long breath in,

00:13:48.914 --> 00:13:50.330
and then what we're
going to do is

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:53.640
we're going to purse our
lips and let the air out

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:58.570
through our lips,
if people can see.

00:13:58.570 --> 00:14:03.090
And you're pushing it
as long as you can.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:05.840
Just a long exhale.

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:09.680
And you just let the tension
go out with your breath.

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:10.930
OK.

00:14:10.930 --> 00:14:20.880
So let's take a deep
breath in and pause

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:23.190
and let the breath out
through your pursed lips.

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:47.800
Take another deep breath in.

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:49.550
And you can do this
on your own pace.

00:14:49.550 --> 00:14:53.720
Don't feel like
you have to wait.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:55.080
And take a pause.

00:15:18.115 --> 00:15:20.781
And then I'm going to ask you to
do three more on your own pace.

00:16:18.630 --> 00:16:22.790
Appreciate you doing
all that with me.

00:16:22.790 --> 00:16:30.060
And then we're gonna count
from five to one, and at one,

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:33.340
please open your eyes and
bring your attention back

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:35.800
to the front of the room.

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:44.704
Five, four, three, two, one.

00:16:50.220 --> 00:16:51.280
Thank you.

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:55.608
I notice that people's
expressions seem more relaxed.

00:16:55.608 --> 00:16:58.300
Yeah.

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:00.785
I'm gonna pass it
over to Sharon.

00:17:00.785 --> 00:17:02.160
SHARON SALZBERG:
It was at Google

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:04.544
that I first heard the term OG.

00:17:04.544 --> 00:17:05.710
I had no idea what it means.

00:17:05.710 --> 00:17:08.077
Do you all know what it means?

00:17:08.077 --> 00:17:09.660
See, not everyone
knows what it means.

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:10.785
It means original gangster.

00:17:12.947 --> 00:17:15.030
This is the first time
anyone ever called me that.

00:17:15.030 --> 00:17:16.750
And I prize it.

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:18.975
Everywhere I go I say, you
know the best introduction

00:17:18.975 --> 00:17:20.107
I ever had?

00:17:20.107 --> 00:17:20.815
It was at Google.

00:17:20.815 --> 00:17:22.000
It was Bill Duane.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:23.240
He called me an OG.

00:17:28.369 --> 00:17:34.010
So I did go to India quite a
number of years ago in 1970.

00:17:34.010 --> 00:17:36.830
Came back in 1974 as
a meditation teacher,

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:38.760
a mindfulness teacher.

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:44.240
And it's kind of extraordinary,
of course, to see the wave,

00:17:44.240 --> 00:17:47.260
and to see the new
prominence of the word.

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:51.850
And one of the concerns I have
about the word mindfulness

00:17:51.850 --> 00:17:55.670
and the implications it
might have for people

00:17:55.670 --> 00:17:59.640
is a kind of passivity,
you know, or complacency.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:04.820
Like in a kind of immediate
way, I was leading a meditation

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:08.760
once, and we began
with listening to sound

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:10.530
before moving to the breath.

00:18:10.530 --> 00:18:15.460
And I got no further than,
listen to the sound and someone

00:18:15.460 --> 00:18:17.700
raised their hand
and said, well,

00:18:17.700 --> 00:18:20.800
what if it's the sound of
the smoke alarm going off?

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:22.780
Should I sit here
mindfully knowing

00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:25.050
the smoke alarm is going off?

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:26.250
Or should I get up?

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:28.600
And I said, I'd get up.

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:35.200
But the ways mindfulness
is defined correctly

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:37.410
often brings a kind
of confusion just

00:18:37.410 --> 00:18:41.230
because of the associations
we have with the word.

00:18:41.230 --> 00:18:45.680
Mindfulness means accepting
things the way that they are.

00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:50.280
Mindfulness means being with
things without judgment.

00:18:50.280 --> 00:18:52.660
Kind of sounds like
you're going to sit there

00:18:52.660 --> 00:18:55.020
with the smoke alarm going off.

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:57.720
So metaphorically, I think
that's a good picture

00:18:57.720 --> 00:18:58.810
of our time.

00:18:58.810 --> 00:19:01.140
There are lots of
alarms going off.

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:06.659
And sometimes we can think,
oh, something like mindfulness

00:19:06.659 --> 00:19:08.950
is going to give me the
ability-- it's like Bill said--

00:19:08.950 --> 00:19:10.870
to sort of number out.

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:13.250
I'm going to just accept
things the way that they are.

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:16.740
I'm going to just be with
things without judgment.

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:19.660
And it's not quite
like sitting there

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:24.600
with the smoke alarm going
off being passive at all.

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:29.350
Really we're talking
about many levels.

00:19:29.350 --> 00:19:32.660
We're talking about having
a dynamic relationship

00:19:32.660 --> 00:19:36.360
with our experience
instead of, perhaps,

00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:38.810
being so caught in habit.

00:19:38.810 --> 00:19:42.210
We're talking about, just
as Phoenix was saying,

00:19:42.210 --> 00:19:48.150
finding a place in the middle
where we're not necessarily

00:19:48.150 --> 00:19:52.310
consumed by what's going on
because that really debilitates

00:19:52.310 --> 00:19:55.400
us, or devastates us,
and doesn't necessarily

00:19:55.400 --> 00:19:57.990
give us any room to act.

00:19:57.990 --> 00:20:00.850
Nor are we going to
hate it and fear it

00:20:00.850 --> 00:20:05.340
as a kind of cultivation,
like, you know,

00:20:05.340 --> 00:20:07.300
I've been meditating
for 45 years.

00:20:07.300 --> 00:20:10.030
I shouldn't feel this kind
of thing anymore, dammit.

00:20:10.030 --> 00:20:11.300
You know?

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.680
It's just not useful,
either extreme.

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:18.860
And so there's a kind of
creativity in that energy.

00:20:18.860 --> 00:20:23.700
And I feel it is very aligned
with the power of love

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:25.940
or the power of compassion.

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:29.120
I think one of the things I've
done in meditation practice,

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:31.592
or we do in any kind
of introspection

00:20:31.592 --> 00:20:33.050
when we're really
looking-- doesn't

00:20:33.050 --> 00:20:36.840
have to be meditation-- is
I felt like I really looked

00:20:36.840 --> 00:20:41.220
at all the things--
probably not all,

00:20:41.220 --> 00:20:47.320
but many of the things that
I'd been told were true.

00:20:47.320 --> 00:20:50.000
Where does strength lie?

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:53.740
How alone am I?

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:57.240
What are the
divisions between us?

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:59.300
What's the reality?

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:02.810
Is a quality like
love or compassion

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:08.680
really as foolish and gooey and
sentimental and weak as I've

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:10.580
been taught?

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:19.470
Is vengefulness and hatred as
strong as I need in this time?

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:21.890
So I feel one of the
greatest gifts I've

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:25.070
gotten from my own
practice is that ability

00:21:25.070 --> 00:21:27.330
to look with a kind
of rigor and honesty.

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:30.160
And it needs a
lot of compassion,

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:33.310
because it's not always
easy, what we see

00:21:33.310 --> 00:21:36.520
in terms of our conditioning.

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:43.350
I feel like there's
a core within all

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:50.100
of that of recognizing
our wish to be happy,

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:54.510
to feel a sense of belonging
in this body and this mind

00:21:54.510 --> 00:22:00.180
with one another, a
sense of home somewhere.

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:04.975
And even more than that,
almost like the right to that,

00:22:04.975 --> 00:22:08.630
no matter who we are, no
matter what others tell us

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:12.700
about us, whatever stories
are told about us, that that

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:15.100
is really at the
core of our being.

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:21.380
And so I think mindfulness
is very connected to that

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:25.640
as well, as we practice.

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:28.010
And again, we can
practice mindfulness

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:29.250
a million different ways.

00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:30.958
It doesn't have to be
through meditation.

00:22:30.958 --> 00:22:35.130
But it's that quality
of looking and looking

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:38.620
with a kind of
sense of your own,

00:22:38.620 --> 00:22:44.270
I'd say, innate dignity, that we
do deserve a kind of happiness.

00:22:44.270 --> 00:22:51.520
And so I've practiced
with striking fast food

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:56.390
workers, for example, striking
for $15 an hour minimum wage,

00:22:56.390 --> 00:23:04.180
and who are risking everything,
everything in their lives

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:09.130
to sort take a stand and say,
I have some worth as person.

00:23:12.340 --> 00:23:18.470
I've sat with people
who have been subjected

00:23:18.470 --> 00:23:21.330
to incredible violence,
or their families,

00:23:21.330 --> 00:23:29.240
and have watched in awe
as people have tried

00:23:29.240 --> 00:23:36.990
to work through where their
ultimate happiness might lie,

00:23:36.990 --> 00:23:45.530
and how they might reweave
the story of what's

00:23:45.530 --> 00:23:49.700
possible for a human
being based on the things

00:23:49.700 --> 00:23:53.270
that they've gone
through and their wish

00:23:53.270 --> 00:23:56.460
to make this a better world,
and not just kind of cycle

00:23:56.460 --> 00:24:01.370
down and endlessly spiral down.

00:24:01.370 --> 00:24:04.260
There are a lot of admirable
people in this world, I find.

00:24:04.260 --> 00:24:09.964
We don't often hear about them,
perhaps, which is a problem.

00:24:09.964 --> 00:24:15.050
But for me, the core of my
being able to venture forth

00:24:15.050 --> 00:24:20.830
into some of these
terrains is-- having

00:24:20.830 --> 00:24:25.750
had some shit happen
in my own life-- has

00:24:25.750 --> 00:24:28.430
been really the
offering of some tools

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:32.020
so that these aren't
just idealistic notions.

00:24:32.020 --> 00:24:36.850
And it certainly isn't
leading to a kind of passivity

00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:42.020
or complacency, but
really some tools

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:50.840
to help me see through kind
of the myths I've been given,

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:53.890
work out of them, find
sources of strength

00:24:53.890 --> 00:24:57.900
that I never imagined
were strong at all,

00:24:57.900 --> 00:25:00.970
which is why I teach quite
a lot of loving kindness

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:03.697
meditation, which maybe we'll
do toward the end of our time

00:25:03.697 --> 00:25:04.280
here together.

00:25:07.210 --> 00:25:15.290
And of all techniques,
it's one where people often

00:25:15.290 --> 00:25:19.019
approach it in the beginning
is, like, that's stupid.

00:25:19.019 --> 00:25:20.310
How can that make a difference?

00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:26.070
But like all things,
it's an experiment.

00:25:26.070 --> 00:25:29.060
You know, it takes
a little risk taking

00:25:29.060 --> 00:25:31.300
to see for yourself
if this is something

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:34.810
that might be onward leaning.

00:25:34.810 --> 00:25:38.920
It does begin, I think, with
a kind of self-knowledge

00:25:38.920 --> 00:25:45.170
that is very personal.

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:46.200
It's very insightful.

00:25:46.200 --> 00:25:52.760
And this is really one of the
greatest powers of mindfulness.

00:25:52.760 --> 00:25:54.510
These days when we
talk about mindfulness,

00:25:54.510 --> 00:26:00.970
mostly we talk about things like
really enjoying your cup of tea

00:26:00.970 --> 00:26:02.870
because you're
actually tasting it.

00:26:02.870 --> 00:26:06.320
You're not so
crazily multitasking

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:08.170
while you drink the cup of tea.

00:26:08.170 --> 00:26:10.040
And that's really good.

00:26:10.040 --> 00:26:14.070
But classically, the
main goal of mindfulness

00:26:14.070 --> 00:26:17.300
is to reveal our
lives to ourselves,

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:22.150
to understand so much more
about what's motivating us,

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:25.950
and what's onward leading,
and what's really bringing us

00:26:25.950 --> 00:26:29.020
down, or even crushing us.

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:31.140
And then we know so much.

00:26:31.140 --> 00:26:36.540
So one exercise I thought
we could do before we go on

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:44.810
is sit together
for a little bit,

00:26:44.810 --> 00:26:48.880
have each person explore some
of the emotional terrain you've

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:53.350
experienced recently,
whatever that might be,

00:26:53.350 --> 00:27:01.940
choose one really predominant
emotion, and look inside it.

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:04.960
Not why is it here, and what
am I going to do about it,

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:07.940
and should I switch therapists
or whatever, but you

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:10.050
know, what is this feeling?

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:13.650
First, what is it in my body?

00:27:13.650 --> 00:27:16.300
And just take note of that.

00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:21.930
And then see if you can watch
the movie of that feeling.

00:27:21.930 --> 00:27:24.542
Sometimes if I'm working with
people over a period of time,

00:27:24.542 --> 00:27:26.250
let's say it's something
like-- let's say

00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:30.790
it's anger-- I'll say
next time we meet,

00:27:30.790 --> 00:27:32.750
see if you can tell
me three things you

00:27:32.750 --> 00:27:38.700
found inside the anger, and
one of them can be change.

00:27:38.700 --> 00:27:40.160
Maybe there's sadness in there.

00:27:40.160 --> 00:27:41.770
Maybe there's fear in there.

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:47.010
Very, very commonly, there is a
sense of hopelessness in there.

00:27:47.010 --> 00:27:49.350
So just a few things.

00:27:49.350 --> 00:27:53.160
And whatever is in
there, it's changing.

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:57.400
It's coming, it's going,
it's actually fluid, however

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:02.270
static or concrete we might
take it superficially.

00:28:02.270 --> 00:28:04.200
So we'll do a little
bit of that together.

00:28:04.200 --> 00:28:10.380
And then for those of you
who are, after the exercise,

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:11.806
going to be writing,
you can just

00:28:11.806 --> 00:28:12.930
write it down for yourself.

00:28:12.930 --> 00:28:15.550
Those of you who are here,
you can either write,

00:28:15.550 --> 00:28:21.380
or we'll have you just speak
to one another if you wish.

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:22.610
OK?

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:25.550
So let's sit together.

00:28:25.550 --> 00:28:28.746
And going back to the
refuge that is the breath,

00:28:28.746 --> 00:28:29.995
because it really is a refuge.

00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:37.595
As my early teachers
would say, you

00:28:37.595 --> 00:28:40.095
don't have to believe anything
in order to feel your breath.

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:44.670
You don't have to
call yourself, you

00:28:44.670 --> 00:28:49.030
know, I'm Buddhist or Hindu,
or reject anything else.

00:28:49.030 --> 00:28:52.930
If you're breathing,
you can be meditating.

00:28:52.930 --> 00:28:55.630
And as one teacher said--
I've always really thought

00:28:55.630 --> 00:29:00.080
it was charming-- he said
the breath is very portable.

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:00.800
Right?

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:03.440
So you practice now.

00:29:03.440 --> 00:29:06.047
We'll practice just
for a few minutes.

00:29:06.047 --> 00:29:07.880
But then you're at work,
or you're somewhere

00:29:07.880 --> 00:29:11.600
where it's very stressful,
or you're commuting,

00:29:11.600 --> 00:29:13.110
and you're getting
really anxious,

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:14.690
and you're getting
really harried.

00:29:14.690 --> 00:29:16.930
You can breathe.

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:19.030
Just rest of your
attention on the breath.

00:29:19.030 --> 00:29:24.630
So it's right there for you as
a way of getting some space.

00:29:24.630 --> 00:29:26.720
So again, you can have
your eyes open or closed,

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:30.470
however you feel most at ease.

00:29:30.470 --> 00:29:33.170
See if you can find the place
where the breath is clearest

00:29:33.170 --> 00:29:34.770
for you or strongest for you.

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:56.380
Maybe the nostrils, the
chest, or the abdomen.

00:29:56.380 --> 00:29:57.690
Find that place.

00:29:57.690 --> 00:30:01.640
Bring your attention
there and just rest.

00:30:01.640 --> 00:30:03.122
See if you can feel one breath.

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:13.380
And if you find your
attention wandering,

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:14.503
don't worry about it.

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:21.840
Maybe your mind has jumped
to the past or the future,

00:30:21.840 --> 00:30:25.210
judgement, speculation,
or you've fallen asleep.

00:30:25.210 --> 00:30:26.230
Really, it's OK.

00:30:30.220 --> 00:30:32.950
See if you can let go of
whatever has distracted you.

00:30:32.950 --> 00:30:34.624
Let go gently.

00:30:34.624 --> 00:30:36.040
And just bring
your attention back

00:30:36.040 --> 00:30:37.248
to the feeling of the breath.

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:25.440
And see if you can bring to
mind just an array of emotions

00:32:25.440 --> 00:32:28.830
you've felt in the
last week or two,

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:33.026
just what flashes through
you as you contemplate that.

00:32:40.840 --> 00:32:49.530
It could be anything, from
anger to boredom, whatever.

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:24.430
And then choose one or two--
certainly one at a time--

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:28.640
and actually enhance it.

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:29.780
Strengthen it.

00:33:29.780 --> 00:33:31.562
See what it feels
like in your body.

00:33:41.230 --> 00:33:44.580
And to do this, clearly
you can't be lost

00:33:44.580 --> 00:33:47.190
and, you know, this is the only
thing I'll ever feel forever,

00:33:47.190 --> 00:33:48.980
or this is wrong to feel.

00:33:48.980 --> 00:33:51.566
This is an experiment.

00:33:51.566 --> 00:33:53.065
What does it feel
like in your body?

00:34:22.250 --> 00:34:26.840
Then observe the movie of
it, the unfolding of it.

00:34:26.840 --> 00:34:29.420
What do you see within it?

00:34:29.420 --> 00:34:30.210
Just watch.

00:34:32.929 --> 00:34:34.230
See what might emerge.

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:48.490
And remember that no
matter what you discover,

00:35:48.490 --> 00:35:51.970
one of the characteristics
is going to be change.

00:35:51.970 --> 00:35:54.059
It's going to be impermanence.

00:35:54.059 --> 00:35:55.142
It's going to be movement.

00:36:58.990 --> 00:37:00.998
Now when you feel ready,
you can open your eyes.

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:15.220
If you want to take
a few moments just

00:37:15.220 --> 00:37:19.261
to reflect on what you
saw, maybe write it down.

00:37:19.261 --> 00:37:20.760
I don't know if
there's anybody here

00:37:20.760 --> 00:37:24.480
who wants to speak to the
person next to them or not.

00:37:32.730 --> 00:37:34.850
I feel I've learned
some much myself

00:37:34.850 --> 00:37:38.930
in doing that kind of
exercise, like look at how much

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:41.760
loneliness there
is in that desire.

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:45.160
Look at how much hopelessness
there is in that anger.

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:08.380
So I think we'll
take a few minutes

00:38:08.380 --> 00:38:13.620
for questions or comments before
we go on with the program.

00:38:13.620 --> 00:38:16.350
AUDIENCE: I was trying
to focus on what

00:38:16.350 --> 00:38:19.330
