00:54:03.813 --> 00:54:05.830
could lead someone to do that.

00:54:05.830 --> 00:54:08.290
And again, it was
another paradox there,

00:54:08.290 --> 00:54:11.130
because I was like, I
could tell her stories.

00:54:11.130 --> 00:54:13.250
I could tell her so many
stories of young people

00:54:13.250 --> 00:54:17.050
who are paying rent, or
who are homeless and are

00:54:17.050 --> 00:54:19.650
trying to figure out how
to make food-- to eat.

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:21.690
But at the same
time, in that moment,

00:54:21.690 --> 00:54:24.920
was someone with a cast.

00:54:24.920 --> 00:54:26.900
And I was like this
is not the time

00:54:26.900 --> 00:54:30.360
for me to bring in their story.

00:54:30.360 --> 00:54:33.330
She needs to heal before
she can have space to hear.

00:54:33.330 --> 00:54:37.350
So that's what I'm talking about
when I'm talking about what

00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:39.370
we need in this society.

00:54:39.370 --> 00:54:45.200
I think we're all walking around
with casts in different ways.

00:54:45.200 --> 00:54:49.520
And we're also all walking
around with so much love.

00:54:49.520 --> 00:54:53.290
And then that is so bad,
I just don't have space,

00:54:53.290 --> 00:54:54.310
and I shut down.

00:54:54.310 --> 00:54:57.540
And all the beautiful parts
of me aren't available.

00:54:57.540 --> 00:55:00.960
And how do we work
with all this?

00:55:00.960 --> 00:55:04.270
And that's what we do here.

00:55:04.270 --> 00:55:08.320
We sit in it, so that we're not
just going to the next thing

00:55:08.320 --> 00:55:09.410
and not processing.

00:55:09.410 --> 00:55:12.250
We're sitting here and
we're being with it.

00:55:12.250 --> 00:55:14.220
SHARON SALZBERG:
Certainly in this society

00:55:14.220 --> 00:55:16.530
there's a tremendous
phobia about looking

00:55:16.530 --> 00:55:18.770
at pain and suffering.

00:55:18.770 --> 00:55:22.560
If it's your own, it's
cast as something shameful

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:24.230
or to be avoided.

00:55:24.230 --> 00:55:26.627
If it's someone else's,
you'd rather tuck him

00:55:26.627 --> 00:55:28.210
away soon so you
don't have to see it,

00:55:28.210 --> 00:55:32.140
it's so unseemly that you are
displaying such suffering.

00:55:32.140 --> 00:55:41.178
And that's a struggle many of
us have with our conditioning.

00:55:41.178 --> 00:55:44.470
And interestingly enough,
I find myself these days

00:55:44.470 --> 00:55:50.500
also talking a lot
about the relationship

00:55:50.500 --> 00:55:54.910
we might have to joy and
pleasure and happiness,

00:55:54.910 --> 00:55:57.710
not just because my books
are all called happy

00:55:57.710 --> 00:56:00.840
something or other,
which are titles

00:56:00.840 --> 00:56:03.263
the publisher
gives them, not me.

00:56:06.467 --> 00:56:07.550
But it's intriguing to me.

00:56:07.550 --> 00:56:09.860
I've spent so much
of my life trying

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:13.980
to come to terms with suffering,
and in a hugely important way,

00:56:13.980 --> 00:56:16.020
you know, what's the
role of compassion,

00:56:16.020 --> 00:56:19.190
rather than all that
separation and so on.

00:56:19.190 --> 00:56:20.730
And it's just been
lately I've also

00:56:20.730 --> 00:56:24.490
been kind of playing a
lot in the fields of joy

00:56:24.490 --> 00:56:25.360
and happiness.

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:29.970
And part of it is also part
of that healing in this time,

00:56:29.970 --> 00:56:36.920
because it feels so wrong,
somehow, to just take a moment

00:56:36.920 --> 00:56:37.940
and enjoy something.

00:56:37.940 --> 00:56:40.279
But in the end, we're
talking about balance.

00:56:40.279 --> 00:56:41.570
We're talking about resilience.

00:56:41.570 --> 00:56:45.380
We're talking about having
some sense of inner resource

00:56:45.380 --> 00:56:47.780
so we don't feel so
utterly depleted,

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:51.630
because if we do feel utterly
depleted and overwhelmed

00:56:51.630 --> 00:56:54.960
and shattered, we don't
have the wherewithal

00:56:54.960 --> 00:56:57.550
to actually try to
make a difference

00:56:57.550 --> 00:56:59.400
or even keep tuning in.

00:56:59.400 --> 00:57:01.510
It's like too much.

00:57:01.510 --> 00:57:05.330
I was talking to Bill before
a little bit about Russia.

00:57:05.330 --> 00:57:08.800
And I always think about this
time I went to the Soviet

00:57:08.800 --> 00:57:12.690
Union--it was still Soviet
Union in those days,

00:57:12.690 --> 00:57:18.360
a long time ago in the '80s--
and I went with my friend,

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:20.740
my colleague, Joseph
Goldstein, to teach.

00:57:20.740 --> 00:57:24.300
And it was actually illegal to
teach meditation in those days.

00:57:24.300 --> 00:57:26.660
So we went as part
of a tour group.

00:57:26.660 --> 00:57:29.800
And we even brought Joseph's
mother as kind of cover,

00:57:29.800 --> 00:57:31.710
so no one would know
what we were doing.

00:57:31.710 --> 00:57:35.290
And every afternoon we
would disappear, he and I,

00:57:35.290 --> 00:57:38.110
and we would go off
with a translator

00:57:38.110 --> 00:57:42.146
into someone's living
room, and we would teach.

00:57:42.146 --> 00:57:44.110
And I found myself
speaking a lot

00:57:44.110 --> 00:57:46.600
about compassion in those days.

00:57:46.600 --> 00:57:49.870
And every time I did, I kind
of got this really-- there

00:57:49.870 --> 00:57:51.620
was this really funny
feeling in the room.

00:57:51.620 --> 00:57:53.450
So I finally sat down
with the translator

00:57:53.450 --> 00:57:57.980
and I said, when I say
compassion, what do you say?

00:57:57.980 --> 00:58:00.410
And they said, oh,
it's like this state.

00:58:00.410 --> 00:58:03.510
You're miserable and
you feel horrible,

00:58:03.510 --> 00:58:08.330
and you're broken by the
suffering that you see.

00:58:08.330 --> 00:58:11.930
And it's like someone
has taken a giant stake

00:58:11.930 --> 00:58:14.520
and driven it
through your heart.

00:58:14.520 --> 00:58:17.010
And I thought, no wonder
there's a really funny feeling

00:58:17.010 --> 00:58:18.190
in the room.

00:58:18.190 --> 00:58:19.850
And it's like, oh.

00:58:19.850 --> 00:58:23.210
But we can actually be
pretty close to that.

00:58:23.210 --> 00:58:25.020
And it's not selfish.

00:58:25.020 --> 00:58:26.240
It's not self-centered.

00:58:26.240 --> 00:58:31.390
It's not weird to feel I need
a different kind of balance,

00:58:31.390 --> 00:58:31.890
you know?

00:58:31.890 --> 00:58:36.180
I need something that
is more uplifting,

00:58:36.180 --> 00:58:42.570
that will give me that kind
of resilience and help me.

00:58:42.570 --> 00:58:44.190
So that's very, very important.

00:58:44.190 --> 00:58:49.200
And I did a program-- it was
a four-year program working

00:58:49.200 --> 00:58:55.460
with frontline domestic
violence shelter workers.

00:58:55.460 --> 00:59:00.250
And we asked in the beginning--
it was actually interesting

00:59:00.250 --> 00:59:02.410
just in the context
of work-- so we said,

00:59:02.410 --> 00:59:05.200
what's your greatest
stressor at work?

00:59:05.200 --> 00:59:07.830
And this was all written so
you didn't have to disclose

00:59:07.830 --> 00:59:09.150
anything if you didn't want.

00:59:09.150 --> 00:59:10.816
And that was interesting,
because people

00:59:10.816 --> 00:59:13.100
who did choose to
speak would sometimes

00:59:13.100 --> 00:59:16.760
say surprising things,
like colleagues,

00:59:16.760 --> 00:59:22.860
not sort of the hideous
workload or something.

00:59:22.860 --> 00:59:24.580
But it was interesting
to look at.

00:59:24.580 --> 00:59:26.190
And then the second
column was, what

00:59:26.190 --> 00:59:30.870
do you do to kind of lift
your spirits, or get a break,

00:59:30.870 --> 00:59:34.060
or get some
perspective on things?

00:59:34.060 --> 00:59:36.070
And they'd write them down.

00:59:36.070 --> 00:59:40.220
And then the third
column was, how do you

00:59:40.220 --> 00:59:43.316
feel about the things you wrote
down in the second column?

00:59:43.316 --> 00:59:48.790
So every single person, as far
as I know, through four years,

00:59:48.790 --> 00:59:51.290
in that second column,
wrote down music.

00:59:51.290 --> 00:59:53.100
It was all different
kinds of music,

00:59:53.100 --> 00:59:56.200
but everybody wrote
down listening to music.

00:59:56.200 --> 00:59:59.220
For some people they
were quote religious.

00:59:59.220 --> 01:00:01.220
Other people it was nature.

01:00:01.220 --> 01:00:03.525
And this is New York City,
you know, it's very gritty.

01:00:06.360 --> 01:00:10.720
And sometimes people looked
at that second column

01:00:10.720 --> 01:00:12.910
and they said, that's
what really helps me.

01:00:12.910 --> 01:00:14.860
I'm not doing any of that.

01:00:14.860 --> 01:00:16.420
That's not good.

01:00:16.420 --> 01:00:18.780
Or maybe they wrote
down, I drink a lot.

01:00:18.780 --> 01:00:21.160
And they'd say, I'm doing
a little too much of that.

01:00:21.160 --> 01:00:25.170
Maybe I need to stop that.

01:00:25.170 --> 01:00:27.230
And one woman who
did read her thing,

01:00:27.230 --> 01:00:31.570
she said, I watch a lot
of "American Idol," which

01:00:31.570 --> 01:00:32.800
I laughed.

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:35.010
I said, oh, I saw that once.

01:00:35.010 --> 01:00:37.410
I got unbelievably stressed out.

01:00:37.410 --> 01:00:40.820
For me it was like watching
continual rejection, you know?

01:00:40.820 --> 01:00:43.560
There's not a way in the
world that, for me, it

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:45.450
would have helped.

01:00:45.450 --> 01:00:48.550
And then we just said,
OK, here are these tools.

01:00:48.550 --> 01:00:51.450
If you want to experiment
with them, here's meditation.

01:00:51.450 --> 01:00:52.310
Here's yoga.

01:00:52.310 --> 01:00:55.300
Here are these other things you
might try, because in the end,

01:00:55.300 --> 01:01:01.890
you cannot go on in a good way
without both a sense of relief

01:01:01.890 --> 01:01:06.980
and some experience of joy,
which could be very immediate,

01:01:06.980 --> 01:01:12.340
somebody's smile, or a friend,
or something that will really

01:01:12.340 --> 01:01:13.839
help us.

01:01:13.839 --> 01:01:15.880
PHOENIX SOLEIL: And I
think that's why what we're

01:01:15.880 --> 01:01:20.280
doing here is so important.

01:01:20.280 --> 01:01:23.625
We talked about-- when we
were thinking about today,

01:01:23.625 --> 01:01:27.490
it was like, well, when do
we want to have a dialogue?

01:01:27.490 --> 01:01:31.540
When do we want to-- and it's so
important that that be set up.

01:01:31.540 --> 01:01:34.870
And it also is important
that-- it's at a time--

01:01:34.870 --> 01:01:37.750
because what I was saying
about walking around

01:01:37.750 --> 01:01:44.080
with casts-- with what's
happening in the news,

01:01:44.080 --> 01:01:46.310
I think it's like getting hit.

01:01:46.310 --> 01:01:48.930
It's being really
emotionally hit.

01:01:48.930 --> 01:01:52.660
And so we really need to
take care of ourselves.

01:01:52.660 --> 01:01:54.640
And it's not being selfish.

01:01:54.640 --> 01:01:56.530
It's getting prepared.

01:01:56.530 --> 01:01:59.420
It's like clearing
the space so that we

01:01:59.420 --> 01:02:02.430
can have those dialogues and
we can take those actions,

01:02:02.430 --> 01:02:07.320
because I think all of us
want to create a better world.

01:02:07.320 --> 01:02:18.000
And there's just different ways
of how to get ourselves healed,

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.600
how to heal the emotional
casts that we're in,

01:02:20.600 --> 01:02:23.800
and these are one of the tools.

01:02:23.800 --> 01:02:26.160
And some of it is being
able to take a break

01:02:26.160 --> 01:02:29.490
and see the beauty in the world.

01:02:29.490 --> 01:02:34.850
It's good for me to remember, no
matter what the headlines are,

01:02:34.850 --> 01:02:37.060
there are hummingbirds.

01:02:37.060 --> 01:02:38.660
There's water.

01:02:38.660 --> 01:02:41.400
There's waves, there's the sun.

01:02:41.400 --> 01:02:46.060
We're on a huge rock
orbiting a fireball.

01:02:50.150 --> 01:02:51.290
Let's make this more fun.

01:02:56.410 --> 01:02:59.680
SHARON SALZBERG: So this
is its own distinct method

01:02:59.680 --> 01:03:05.810
of meditation, where rather
than resting our attention

01:03:05.810 --> 01:03:09.650
in the feeling of the breath,
the sensations of the breath,

01:03:09.650 --> 01:03:12.640
we rest our attention
in the silent repetition

01:03:12.640 --> 01:03:14.220
of certain phrases.

01:03:14.220 --> 01:03:19.950
So the phrases are ways of
paying attention differently.

01:03:19.950 --> 01:03:24.630
So for example, if you
are in the habit of kind

01:03:24.630 --> 01:03:26.900
of looking at yourself
at the end of the day

01:03:26.900 --> 01:03:28.670
almost as though to
evaluate yourself,

01:03:28.670 --> 01:03:30.440
like how did I do today?

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:33.379
And let's say you have the habit
of pretty well only remembering

01:03:33.379 --> 01:03:35.420
the mistakes you made and
the things you could've

01:03:35.420 --> 01:03:40.950
done better, and what you didn't
really like, let's just say.

01:03:40.950 --> 01:03:43.730
So much so that your whole
sense of who you are,

01:03:43.730 --> 01:03:46.470
and all that you
will ever be, just

01:03:46.470 --> 01:03:48.510
collapses around that
really stupid thing

01:03:48.510 --> 01:03:50.550
you said at lunch and a meeting.

01:03:50.550 --> 01:03:53.790
So the practice of loving
kindness is one of gift giving.

01:03:53.790 --> 01:03:56.290
It's offering wishing well.

01:03:56.290 --> 01:04:00.010
So instead of fixating
on all those mistakes,

01:04:00.010 --> 01:04:05.530
we kind of expand our sense of
who we are, like anything good

01:04:05.530 --> 01:04:07.280
happen today?

01:04:07.280 --> 01:04:09.930
Any good within me?

01:04:09.930 --> 01:04:14.260
And it's not meant to be
deluded or wishful thinking.

01:04:14.260 --> 01:04:16.850
You're not insisting, oh, wasn't
that a brilliant, witty thing

01:04:16.850 --> 01:04:17.570
I said at lunch?

01:04:17.570 --> 01:04:20.880
Maybe it was really stupid, and
there are consequences to that.

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:25.390
But that's not all that we
are, so it's that collapse.

01:04:25.390 --> 01:04:28.240
So what do we look at?

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:30.480
So we pretty well only
look at what's wrong.

01:04:30.480 --> 01:04:32.020
And who do we look at?

01:04:32.020 --> 01:04:33.480
Who do we look through?

01:04:33.480 --> 01:04:35.270
Who doesn't count?

01:04:35.270 --> 01:04:36.380
Who is the other?

01:04:36.380 --> 01:04:39.940
Not even just by dint
of prejudice or bias,

01:04:39.940 --> 01:04:42.250
but just indifference.

01:04:42.250 --> 01:04:45.990
So what happens when we look at
them rather than through them?

01:04:45.990 --> 01:04:48.360
So all of this is done
through the silent repetition

01:04:48.360 --> 01:04:49.810
of certain phrases.

01:04:49.810 --> 01:04:51.880
Phrases are very simple,
like may I be happy,

01:04:51.880 --> 01:04:53.900
may you be happy.

01:04:53.900 --> 01:04:56.520
Being words, they
are quite imperfect.

01:04:56.520 --> 01:04:58.330
I know that.

01:04:58.330 --> 01:05:02.850
But it's a vehicle for us
to pay attention differently

01:05:02.850 --> 01:05:07.150
and to include where maybe
we've previously excluded,

01:05:07.150 --> 01:05:10.600
or to loosen the grip of
some of those fixations

01:05:10.600 --> 01:05:12.770
on what's wrong and so on.

01:05:12.770 --> 01:05:15.660
So we make that
offering to ourselves,

01:05:15.660 --> 01:05:21.970
to all kinds of different beings
in our sphere, those we like,

01:05:21.970 --> 01:05:24.400
those we don't like that much.

01:05:24.400 --> 01:05:27.065
And we end with all
beings everywhere.

01:05:27.065 --> 01:05:29.060
So there are a million
variations of this,

01:05:29.060 --> 01:05:32.260
and I'll guide you
through one, OK?

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:35.470
So see if you can
sit comfortably.

01:05:35.470 --> 01:05:39.350
You can close your eyes or not.

01:05:39.350 --> 01:05:41.850
Let your energy just
settle in your body.

01:05:52.420 --> 01:05:57.326
See if there are three or four
phrases that make sense to you

01:05:57.326 --> 01:05:58.470
as this kind of offering.

01:05:58.470 --> 01:06:04.280
Common phrases are things
like, beginning with yourself,

01:06:04.280 --> 01:06:15.780
may I be safe, be happy,
be healthy, live with ease.

01:06:15.780 --> 01:06:18.600
Live with ease means that the
things of day to day life,

01:06:18.600 --> 01:06:22.410
like livelihood, like family,
may not be such a struggle.

01:06:22.410 --> 01:06:23.890
May I live with ease.

01:06:23.890 --> 01:06:34.130
May I be safe, be happy,
be healthy, live with ease.

01:06:34.130 --> 01:06:38.170
You can use these phrases or
any phrases that come to mind.

01:06:38.170 --> 01:06:45.980
Just three or four very general,
and repeat them over and over

01:06:45.980 --> 01:06:47.710
again with enough
space and enough

01:06:47.710 --> 01:06:51.780
silence so that it's a rhythm
that's pleasing to you.

01:06:51.780 --> 01:06:53.710
I have a friend who
thought he'd get

01:06:53.710 --> 01:06:55.190
extra credit by
saying more phrases

01:06:55.190 --> 01:06:56.356
if he said them really fast.

01:06:56.356 --> 01:06:58.300
You don't need to do that.

01:06:58.300 --> 01:07:00.900
See if you can gather all your
attention behind one phrase

01:07:00.900 --> 01:07:06.220
at a time, and then the next.

01:07:06.220 --> 01:07:08.440
And the skill set is
really very much the same.

01:07:08.440 --> 01:07:11.850
If your attention
wanders, doesn't matter.

01:07:11.850 --> 01:07:14.956
See if you can gently let
go and just come back.

01:09:03.560 --> 01:09:05.560
And then if there's
a benefactor, someone

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:10.819
who's helped you, maybe mentored
you or inspired you from afar,

01:09:10.819 --> 01:09:12.390
bring them here.

01:09:12.390 --> 01:09:18.729
Maybe say their name to yourself
or get an image of them,

01:09:18.729 --> 01:09:21.550
get a feeling for
their presence.

01:09:21.550 --> 01:09:23.910
And offer these phrases
to them, even again,

01:09:23.910 --> 01:09:28.720
if the phrases aren't perfect,
they're like a vehicle for us,

01:09:28.720 --> 01:09:29.760
they're serving us.

01:10:54.020 --> 01:10:56.780
And then a friend, the first
friend who comes to mind.

01:12:33.520 --> 01:12:39.510
Someone you find slightly
annoying, not really bad, just

01:12:39.510 --> 01:12:42.830
a little bit.

01:12:42.830 --> 01:12:43.780
Just see what happens.

01:14:01.340 --> 01:14:05.870
And all beings everywhere,
all people, all creatures,

01:14:05.870 --> 01:14:07.370
all those in existence.

01:14:07.370 --> 01:14:16.790
May all beings be safe,
be happy, be healthy,

01:14:16.790 --> 01:14:17.700
live with ease.

01:14:57.140 --> 01:14:59.140
And when you feel ready,
you can open your eyes.

01:15:11.785 --> 01:15:13.620
So thank you.

01:15:13.620 --> 01:15:14.637
Thank you.

01:15:14.637 --> 01:15:15.720
PHOENIX SOLEIL: Thank you.

